 Context                                  
                                                                                                                                                                                                            
 User want Obsidian-style force-directed knowledge graph layer on top of existing V2.20 AI 投資委員會 system. Reference: 5 screenshots showing dark canvas with pale-grey nodes (tickers MSFT/TSM/AVGO +
 concept nodes capex_supercycle, ai-supply-chain, hbm_base_die_n3_pull_through), edges between them, node size by centrality.
                                          
 Why now: existing V2.X analyzes individual stocks well, but lacks 全域空間感知 (global spatial awareness). Daily news + theme detector + sector intel + deep dives already produce structured artifacts —
 what's missing is the edge layer that surfaces 2nd-order beneficiaries (e.g., NVDA capex story → VRT/COHR/GLW supply chain) and renders narrative共振 visually before financial outcomes confirm them.
                                     
 Intended outcome: new /graph.html Dashboard page showing the knowledge graph; daily-refreshed via daily_update.sh Step 7; centrality scores readable via /api/graph/centrality/<TICKER>. Decision-layer
 untouched in MVP (exploration phase per user preference — graph is for human eyeballing first, Arbiter wiring deferred to V3.1).

 Core Principle (Project Identity)

 Nexus is news- + financial-analysis-driven, not a stock-screener add-on. Its job: synthesize sector intel + news digests + deep-dive narratives + earnings transcripts + thematic reports through LLM
 analysis to surface 1st-order / 2nd-order / 3rd-order relationships between tickers, themes, and catalysts.

 - 1st-order: ticker ↔ direct catalyst (e.g., NVDA ← FY27Q1 earnings)
 - 2nd-order: ticker ↔ supply-chain / theme共振 beneficiary (e.g., NVDA capex → VRT cooling, COHR optics)
 - 3rd-order: cross-theme bridge (e.g., AI capex → power grid bottleneck → GEV / VST utility uplift)

 Tier 3 LLM is the heart, not a supplement. Tier 1 (structured JSON) anchors the graph; Tier 2 (regex) cheap-fills the gaps; Tier 3 carries the structural discovery load — it reads the prose where
 2nd/3rd-order relationships actually live (deep-dive narratives, news debate_notes, sector divergence sections).

